english which to speakers in north america and britain will sound oddly formal. another source of fascination and intrigue for travelers is the ubiquitous use of english for cute quips in random places. one relatively common traffic sign reads, "speed thrills, but kills". on the back of trucks everywhere you'll find "use dipper at night" or "sound horn". however, only standard british english is considered correct. interestingly, keyboards in india are based on the us-standard, so american spelling is also used. indians are adopting more and more native words into their english. a lot of these are already well known 